President Barack Obama has proclaimed February 2012 as National Teen Dating Violence Awareness and Prevention Month. The proclamation highlights the alarming number of young people who experience physical, sexual, or emotional abuse in dating relationships. The consequences of dating violence, such as impaired development and physical harm, pose a threat to the health and well-being of teens. The proclamation calls for critical support and services for victims of dating violence and aims to empower teens with tools to cultivate healthy relationships. Despite progress in reducing violence against women, dating violence remains a reality for many young people. The proclamation encourages awareness and action against dating violence through initiatives like the 1is2many campaign. Resources such as the National Dating Abuse Helpline and the Apps Against Abuse technology challenge are mentioned as tools to prevent dating violence. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of breaking the silence about dating abuse and fostering a culture of respect in communities, schools, and homes.